🧠 1. How to know WHAT to copy
🔹 Rule: Depends on build output

Every language/framework produces output in a specific folder

🔵 React / Frontend apps
✅ Check package.json
"scripts": {
  "build": "react-scripts build"
}

👉 Output folder = build/

OR (Vite)

"build": "vite build"

👉 Output = dist/

🔍 How to confirm

Run:

npm run build
ls

👉 You will see:

build/   OR   dist/
✅ So in Docker:
COPY --from=builder /app/build /usr/share/nginx/html

OR

COPY --from=builder /app/dist /usr/share/nginx/html
🔹 Node.js (Backend)

👉 No “build folder” usually

✅ You copy:
COPY . .

👉 Because Node runs source directly

🔹 Python

👉 Same as Node

COPY . .
🔹 Java (VERY IMPORTANT)
✅ Check:
target/ (Maven)
build/ (Gradle)

👉 Output:

target/myapp.jar
✅ Docker:
COPY --from=builder /app/target/myapp.jar app.jar
🔹 Go

👉 Output is binary

go build -o app
✅ Docker:
COPY --from=builder /app/app .
🧠 2. How to know WHERE to copy

This depends on runtime image

🔵 Nginx (Frontend hosting)

Default path:

/usr/share/nginx/html

👉 That’s why:

COPY --from=builder /app/dist /usr/share/nginx/html
🔹 Node.js

Working directory:

WORKDIR /app

👉 So:

COPY . .
🔹 Python

Same:

WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
🔹 Java

Convention:

WORKDIR /app
COPY app.jar app.jar
🔹 Go
WORKDIR /app
COPY app .
🧠 3. How to know nginx.conf location
🔹 Default config path in Nginx:
/etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf

👉 So:

COPY nginx.conf /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf
🔍 How to verify (pro trick)

Run:

docker run -it nginx:alpine sh

Then:

ls /etc/nginx/conf.d/

👉 You’ll see:

default.conf
⚡ Golden DevOps Formula

Whenever you see:

COPY --from=builder X Y

👉 Ask 2 questions:

Where is X created?
build output folder
Where should Y be?
runtime expectation
🔥 Real Example (Your Case)
COPY --from=builder /app/dist /usr/share/nginx/html

✔ /app/dist → created by React/Vite build
✔ /usr/share/nginx/html → Nginx serves static files from here

🚀 Pro-Level Trick (Interview Question)

If confused:

👉 Run inside container
docker run -it <image> sh

Explore:

ls /

👉 Find correct paths yourself (this is how real engineers do)

